<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900703-0065</DOCNO><DOCID>900703-0065.</DOCID><HL>   Probe of Alleged Collusion   By Airlines Is Broadened</HL><DATE>07/03/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12</SO><CO>   UAL</CO><IN>AIRLINES (AIR)</IN><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The Justice Department said it expanded itsinvestigation into possible antitrust violations by majorU.S. airlines.   James Rill, the department's antitrust chief, said thatprosecutors are investigating a pricing arrangement betweentwo airlines whose names he declined to disclose.</LP><TEXT>   The Justice Department is conducting four otherinvestigations of possible anticompetitive activity in theairline industry. These involve the actions of major carriersthat dominate certain large airports, known as hubs; therelationship between airlines and the industry's computerizedclearinghouse for fares; possible collusion related tocertain fare changes made in September 1989; and the buyingand selling of slots at Chicago's O'Hare airport by UnitedAirlines.   Individual airlines under Justice Department scrutiny havedenied any wrongdoing.</TEXT></DOC>